\begin_layout Subsection
Contravariant and covariant components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, we define the inverse basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{*}{E}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{e_{i}\vphantom{\overset{*}{e}_{j}}}{\underbrace{\left(E\delta_{i}\vphantom{\overset{*}{E}\delta_{j}}\right)}}\cdot\underset{\overset{*}{e}_{j}}{\underbrace{\left(\overset{*}{E}\delta_{j}\right)}}=\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on basis 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 are called the contravariant components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{*}{E}$
\end_inset

 are called the covariant components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show that 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\overset{*}{E}=E^{-T}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
E\delta_{i}\cdot\overset{*}{E}\delta_{j}=\delta_{ij}\\
E^{T}\delta^{i}\,\overset{*}{E}\delta_{j}=\delta_{ij}\\
E^{T}\,\overset{*}{E}=I\\
\overset{*}{E}=\left(E^{T}\right)^{-1}=E^{-T}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contravariant components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on basis 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, therefore they are 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{-1}x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariant components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{*}{E}$
\end_inset

, therefore they are: 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{*}{E}^{-1}x=\left(E^{-T}\right)^{-1}x=E^{T}x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is orthonormal, than 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E^{-T}=\overset{*}{E}$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=x^{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The reverse direction is also true, use 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\delta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show how to express 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 using all 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{j}$
\end_inset

 and the Gramian of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G=E^{T}E$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i}=\delta^{i}E^{T}x=\delta^{i}E^{T}E\delta_{j}\delta^{j}E^{-1}x=G_{ij}x^{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=G_{ij}x^{j}$
\end_inset

, using Einstein's summation, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}=\delta^{i}G\delta_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{i}=\delta^{i}E^{-1}x=\delta^{i}E^{-1}E^{-T}\delta_{j}\delta^{j}E^{T}x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E^{-1}E^{-T}=\left(E^{T}E\right)^{-1}=G^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=G^{ij}x_{j}$
\end_inset

, using Einstein's summation, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}=\delta^{i}G^{-1}\delta_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show various ways to express the dot product 
\begin_inset Formula $x\cdot y$
\end_inset

 using contravariant and covariant components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x\cdot y & =x^{T}y\\
 & =x^{T}EE^{-1}y\\
 & =\left(E^{T}x\right)^{T}\cdot E^{-1}y\\
 & =x_{i}y^{i}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, for any basis 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\cdot y=x_{i}y^{i}=x^{i}y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is orthonormal, than 
\begin_inset Formula $x\cdot y=x_{i}y_{i}=x^{i}y^{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And for any basis 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\cdot y=x^{i}y_{i}=g_{ij}x^{i}y^{j}=g^{ij}x_{i}y_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rodrigues' rotation formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show how to write the rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Rot}(\hat{\omega},\theta)$
\end_inset

 as an operator:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, when rotating 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 around the rotation axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}$
\end_inset

, only the perpendicular part of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is rotated.
 If we rotated 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

 degrees, we would get 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\parallel}+\hat{\omega}\times x^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are rotating by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 degrees, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\parallel}+x^{\perp}\cos\theta+\left(\hat{\omega}\times x^{\perp}\right)\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

