\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Cartesian way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Area is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 the area of a parallelogram sharing two vertices with the triangle:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\begin{vmatrix}x & x+\Delta x\\
y & y+\Delta y
\end{vmatrix}=\frac{1}{2}\begin{vmatrix}x & \Delta x\\
y & \Delta y
\end{vmatrix}=\frac{1}{2}\left(xdy-ydx\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us an alternative proof for the planimeter formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Area}(S)=\frac{1}{2}\ointop_{\partial S}\left(xdy-ydx\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will see two ways to derive 
\begin_inset Formula $d\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
By differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\arctan\frac{y}{x}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d\theta & =\frac{1}{x}\cdot\frac{1}{1+\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)^{2}}\,dy-\frac{y}{x^{2}}\,\frac{1}{1+\left(\frac{y}{x}\right)^{2}}\,dx\\
 & =\frac{xdy-ydx}{x^{2}+y^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
By using the area of an infinitesimal triangle:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $ds=\frac{1}{2}r^{2}d\theta$
\end_inset

, therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\theta=\frac{2ds}{r^{2}}=\frac{2\cdot\frac{1}{2}\left(xdy-ydx\right)}{x^{2}+y^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Either way, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\theta=\frac{xdy-ydx}{x^{2}+y^{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since a full circle is made every 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 degrees, we get winding formula, i.e.
 the number of full circles around the origin:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w(\gamma,0)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\intop_{\gamma}\frac{xdy-ydx}{x^{2}+y^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Catenary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pics/catenary1.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find the shape of a rope hanging freely from two points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pics/catenary2.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's look at the forces operating on an arc 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Horizontal forces: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}=T\cos\varphi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vertical forces: 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho sg=T\sin\varphi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the mass density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Divide the equations and get: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tan\varphi=\frac{\rho sg}{T_{0}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{T_{0}}{\rho g}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tan\varphi=\frac{s}{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\tan\varphi=\frac{dy}{dx}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ds=\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right)^{2}}dx$
\end_inset

, we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
dx=\frac{ds}{\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{s}{a}\right)^{2}}}\\
\int dx=a\int\frac{d\left(\frac{s}{a}\right)}{\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{s}{a}\right)^{2}}}\\
x=a\,\mbox{arcsinh}(\frac{s}{a})+c_{1}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we want the catenary to have arc length 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=a\,\sinh\left(\frac{x}{a}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{s}{a}=\sinh\left(\frac{x}{a}\right)\\
y=a\,\cosh\left(\frac{x}{a}\right)+c_{2}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We prefer to express the lowest point in the catenary using 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 If we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, we get the lowest point is 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will find 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 the catenary's depth and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 the catenary's length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{y}{a}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{s}{a}\right)^{2}=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the furthest point right, 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a+h$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\frac{\ell}{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\left(\frac{a+h}{a}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{\nicefrac{\ell}{2}}{a}\right)^{2}=1\\
a^{2}+2ah+h^{2}-\frac{1}{4}\ell^{2}=a^{2}\\
a=\frac{\frac{1}{4}\ell^{2}-h^{2}}{2h}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Newton-Raphson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a function 
\begin_inset Formula $F:\,R^{n}\to R^{n}$
\end_inset

 we want to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\vec{x})=0$
\end_inset

 (Alternatively, if we want to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\vec{x})=\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, define a new function 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{F}(\vec{x})=F(\vec{x})-\vec{y}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Phantom Phantom
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 be a nearby guess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Taylor series expansion,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
F(x_{1})=F(x_{0}+(x_{1}-x_{0})=F(x_{0})+Df\,(x_{1}-x_{0})+o(\left|x_{1}-x_{0}\right|)\\
F(x_{1})\approx Df\,x_{1}-Df\,x_{0}\\
Df\,x_{0}\approx Df\,x_{1}-F(x_{1})\\
x_{0}\approx x_{1}-\left(Df\right)^{-1}F(x_{1})
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this approximation to iteratively correct our initial guess:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i+1}=x_{i}-\left(Df_{x_{i}}\right)^{-1}F(x_{i})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the univariate case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{i+1}=x_{i}-\frac{F(x_{i})}{F'(x_{i})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

